b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Linux now boots on PS5, GTA 5 hits 60 FPS with RT"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Community split: ‘Jailbreak’ hype vs. stability fears"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Sony’s next move could kill (or legitimize) the scene"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["For years, PlayStation modders have treated Sony’s consoles like Fort Knox: impenetrable, frustrating, and ",["$","em",null,{"children":"just"}]," tempting enough to keep trying. This week, the vault cracked—",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.notebookcheck.net/A-modder-has-successfully-ported-Linux-to-the-PS5-running-GTA-5-Enhanced-with-ray-tracing.772302.0.html","children":"a modder successfully booted Linux on the PS5"}],", then flexed by running ",["$","em",null,{"children":"GTA 5 Enhanced Edition"}]," at 60 FPS with ray tracing. The video, shared on ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://twitter.com","children":"Twitter"}],", isn’t just a tech demo; it’s a middle finger to console limitations, wrapped in a question: ",["$","em",null,{"children":"What if your PS5 could actually be a gaming PC?"}],"\nThe answers are messy. ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"Confirmed facts first"}],": Yes, Linux runs. Yes, GTA 5’s Enhanced Edition—modded with ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://reshade.me/","children":"ReShade ray tracing"}],"—hits 60 FPS on PS5 hardware. The modder’s proof-of-concept even handles ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Cyberpunk 2077"}],"’s path tracing, per early leaks. But here’s the ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"COMMUNITY PULSE"}],": Reddit’s r/PS5Mods is split between ‘",["$","em",null,{"children":"finally, my console can do what my PC does’"}]," and ‘",["$","em",null,{"children":"cool, now Sony’s gonna brick our systems."}],"’ Steam Deck owners are smirking; Xbox modders are taking notes.\nThis isn’t just about Linux. It’s about ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"PLAYER EXPECTATION"}],": Gamers have spent a decade watching PCs get mod tools, performance tweaks, and ",["$","em",null,{"children":"actual"}]," next-gen upgrades while consoles stay locked down. When a PS5 can suddenly run ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Elden Ring"}]," with DLSS or ",["$","em",null,{"children":"Starfield"}]," without the 30 FPS cap, the question isn’t ",["$","em",null,{"children":"if"}]," this matters—it’s ",["$","em",null,{"children":"how long until Sony notices"}],"."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/ps5-linux-mod-runs-gta-5-with-ray-tracingwhats-the/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Modders just unlocked the PS5’s PC soul—but will Sony let them keep it?","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"Modders just unlocked the PS5’s PC soul—but will Sony let them keep it?"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["Let’s talk friction. ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"BACKLASH RADAR"}]," is blinking red: Sony’s history with modding is ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.theverge.com/2021/10/5/22709342/sony-ps5-jailbreak-exploit-patched-firmware-update","children":"a graveyard of banned consoles and lawsuits"}],". The PS4’s Linux scene died when firmware 5.05 exploits got patched; the PS3’s ‘OtherOS’ feature was ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2010/04/sony-removes-linux-support-from-ps3-firmware-update/","children":"removed entirely"}]," after hackers abused it. This time, the mod requires a PS5 on firmware 4.03 or lower—meaning most players are already locked out unless they’ve been hoarding unupdated consoles like rare Pokémon cards.\nThen there’s the ",["$","strong",null,{"children":"PATCH TRANSLATOR"}]," reality: Even if this sticks, Linux on PS5 isn’t a magic ‘run any game’ button. Drivers are janky, performance is inconsistent, and good luck getting ","$L14"," titles like ","$L15"," to play nice. The real win? Proof that the PS5’s RDNA 2 GPU and Zen 2 CPU can ","$L16"," handle PC-level mods—if Sony ever allowed it. (Spoiler: They won’t.)\nThe modding community is already whispering about ","$L17","—imagine a PS5 running ","$L18","’s PC version with ray tracing—or ","$L19"," like ","$L1a","’s ","$L1b",". But for now, this is less a revolution and more a ","$L1c"," moment: ","$L1d"," as a technical feat, ","$L1e"," as a sustainable scene. The clock’s ticking until Sony drops a firmware nuke."]}]]}]
